cph2-1.cdninstagram.com&amp;_nc_gid=trZ8tiQ0MlVLtCt3-If0wg&amp;_nc_ss=7a338&amp;oh=00_AfzxYnchOMBtIOA9TFfYENRrRAhQM4ZBNMXaDzj-3Mvsbg&amp;oe=69CA21C3" alt="Slide 3 fra @ibenelmstrom" style="max-width: 48%; margin: 0 1% 8px 0;" /><img src="https://scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.75761-15/503642288_18276408244260294_4389714079299119726_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_e35_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=109&amp;ig_cache_key=MzY1OTAyMjkxMDc5ODk2NzA2MQ%3D%3D.3-ccb7-5&amp;ccb=7-5&amp;_nc_sid=58cdad&amp;efg=eyJ2ZW5jb2RlX3RhZyI6InhwaWRzLjExNjB4MTA3Ni5zZHIuQzMifQ%3D%3D&amp;_nc_ohc=Bn-TWlqoPboQ7kNvwFpPg16&amp;_nc_oc=Adq0QXLuvODqaC--FinxKXW8JqmCFu2Srq5djCwn8GJXUmpyKjrVzHF1gfV8qsD1JII&amp;_nc_ad=z-m&amp;_nc_cid=0&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;se=7&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com&amp;_nc_gid=trZ8tiQ0MlVLtCt3-If0wg&amp;_nc_ss=7a338&amp;oh=00_AfwcaNQSAX7AUghqthtCP2BiwzTGg2KReskGISy0viJxMw&amp;oe=69CA04B3" alt="Slide 4 fra @ibenelmstrom" style="max-width: 48%; margin: 0 1% 8px 0;" /></p><p><strong>🖼️ Slideshow (4 medier)</strong></p><p><strong>@ibenelmstrom</strong></p><p>🤍 Shared Reflection: Intimacy &amp; Publicness<br/>
Sunday 22 June, 16.30-17.30<br/>
📍Koncertkirken Free and open to all<br/>
<br/>
Join us for a collective reflection with artists Lina Hashim and Nikhil Vettukattil, in conversation with researchers Amaru Ibarra Olguín, Iben Bach Elmstrøm, and Joachim Aagaard Friis. The talk will be moderated by Mikkel Bogh, professor of art history at the University of Copenhagen.<br/>
<br/>
Rather than critique or explanation, this gathering offers an open-ended exploration of the overarching theme—intimacy in public—as it resonates through the performances and experiences we share.<br/>
<br/>
—<br/>
Amaru Ibarra Olguín is a PhD candidate in the Department of Arts and Cultural Studies at the University of Copenhagen, based in the section of Theatre and Performance Studies. Her research focuses on contemporary queer feminist Latinx performance, examining how racialized sexuality and gendered<br/>
embodiment are negotiated through the politics and aesthetics of shame.<br/>
<br/>
Iben Bach Elmstrøm is a PhD candidate at the Department of Communication and Arts (IKH) at Roskilde University, where she is researching how art performances can stimulate new forms of meaning and sensibility in public urban space. She has over 15 years of curatorial experience and is presently employed as curator at Kunsthallen Den Frie in Copenhagen.<br/>
<br/>
Joachim Aagaard Friis is a researcher, writer, and curator with a Ph.D. from the University of Agder, Norway, where he conducted practice-based research on ecological and socially sustainable curatorial practices. He has held positions at Agder Art Center and the University of Science and Technology in Trondheim. His work has been published in various journals and magazines.<br/>
<br/>
Mikkel Bogh is a professor of art history at the University of Copenhagen, Department of Arts and Cultural Studies, where he also serves as director of PASS – Centre for Practice-based Art Studies. From 2005 to 2014, he was rector of the Schools of Visual Arts at the Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts, and from 2014 to 2023, he was director of SMK – National Gallery of Denmark.</p><p><a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/DLHdfVpMIOp/">Se slideshow på Instagram</a></p>]]></content:encoded>
